a{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} (BChl {\textless}italic{\textgreater}a{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} ), {\textless}italic{\textgreater}Thermochromatium tepidum{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} (BChl {\textless}italic{\textgreater}a{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} ), {\textless}italic{\textgreater}Chlorobaculum tepidum{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} (BChl {\textless}italic{\textgreater}a + c{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} ) and {\textless}italic{\textgreater}Blastochloris viridis{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} (BChl {\textless}italic{\textgreater}b{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} ) as representative photosynthetic organisms. Proxima Centauri b has only ≈3{\%} of the PAR (400–700 nm) of Earth irradiance, but we found that potential gross photosynthesis ( {\textless}italic{\textgreater}P{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} {\textless}sub{\textgreater}g{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} ) on Proxima Centauri b could be surprisingly high (oxygenic photosynthesis: earth ≈0.8 gC m {\textless}sup{\textgreater}−2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater} h {\textless}sup{\textgreater}−1{\textless}/sup{\textgreater} ; Proxima Centauri b ≈0.14 gC m {\textless}sup{\textgreater}−2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater} h {\textless}sup{\textgreater}−1{\textless}/sup{\textgreater} ). The proportion of PAR irradiance useable by oxygenic photosynthetic organisms (the sum of Blue + Red irradiance) is similar for the Earth and Proxima Centauri b. The oxygenic photic zone would be only ≈10 m deep in water compared with ≈200 m on Earth. The {\textless}italic{\textgreater}P{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} {\textless}sub{\textgreater}g{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} of an anoxic Earth (gC m {\textless}sup{\textgreater}−2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater} h {\textless}sup{\textgreater}−1{\textless}/sup{\textgreater} ) is ≈0.34–0.59 (land) and could be as high as ≈0.29–0.44 on Proxima Centauri b. 1 m of water does not affect oxygenic or anoxygenic photosynthesis on Earth, but on Proxima Centauri b oxygenic {\textless}italic{\textgreater}P{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} {\textless}sub{\textgreater}g{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} is reduced by ≈50{\%}. Effective elimination of near IR limits {\textless}italic{\textgreater}P{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} {\textless}sub{\textgreater}g{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} by photosynthetic bacteria ({\&}lt;10{\%} of the surface value). The spectrum of Proxima Centauri b is unfavourable for anoxygenic aquatic photosynthesis. Nevertheless, a substantial aerobic or anaerobic ecology is possible on Proxima Centauri b. Protocols to recognize the biogenic signature of anoxygenic photosynthesis are needed. {\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
